attributes.Plaque_text: Near This Spot Earl Percy With Reinforcement Planted A Field Piece To Cover The Retreat Of The British Troops April 19 1775
attributes.Monument_History:
The Stone Cannon
The Stone Cannon Is A Granite Replica Of A Revolutionary War Cannon. It Marks The Spot Where
British General Earl Percy Placed One Of Two Field Artillery Pieces To Cover The Retreating British
Troops On 19 April 1775. It Is Inscribed:
Near This Spot
Earl Percy
With Reinforcement
Planted A Field Piece
To Cover The Retreat
Of The
British Troops
April 19 1775
Erected In 1884, The Stone Cannon Was Designed By Edward Griffin Porter. The Cost Of The
Cannon Was $156.40, Excluding The Cost Of The Foundation It Sits On, Lettering, And Gilding Of The
Letters (Which Is Gone.) The Monument Is Located At 1475 Massachusetts Avenue.
At The Time, Some Questioned, “Why Should We Be Interested In Perpetuating The Memory Of A
Fact, Which Resulted In Saving The British Troops From Utter Destruction?” The Reply, “...It Is Not
[Merely] To Perpetuate The Memory Of A Victory Or A Defeat…[but To Transmit] An Intelligent
Comprehension Of A Great Historic Event [That] Can Only Be Understood By Knowing The British
[And] American Positions In That Desperate Struggle.”
Historical Context
On 6 Nov 1883, The Town Of Lexington Appointed The Historical Memorials & Tablets
Committee. This Ad Hoc Committee Was Charged To Determine, Create, And Erect Appropriate
Markers Commemorating Events That Took Place In Lexington On 19 April 1775. Fifteen Hundred
Dollars Were Appropriated For The Project.
The Committee Met 18 Times And Erected 16 Markers At A Cost Of $1493.61. The Committee’s
Final Report States, “Your Committee Have Not Altogether Satisfied Themselves In The Results
Obtained…but They Believe That The Town Has Received A Fair Equivalent For The Money
Expended…”. The Town Voted That The Committee Publish A Report In Booklet Form To Be Sent To
Every Voter In Lexington, Which Cost $38.35. The Committee Was Dissolved In 1885.
Committee Members: Charles A. Staples (Chair), Edward Griffin Porter, William H. Monroe,
Charles A. Wellington, Gershom Swan
Granite & Labor: R. K. Carpenter - $822.76
Monument: Hallowell Granite Co. - $345.40
Horse & Carriage: Willard Walcott - $11.25
Labor & Stock: D. A. Tuttle - $15.00
Labor: C. Ryan - $15.00
Labor: John Hanscom - $7.00
Cement: W. A. Pierce - $8.00
Painting: J. S. Merriam - $27.50
Designing: Geo. Stotman - 67.50
Carving Tablets: A. Lees - 116.00
Printing 1,000 Reports: Middlesex Townsman - $29.35
Stamps & Envelopes: L.a. Saville - $9.00

attributes.Plaque_text: These Basketball Courts Are Named In Honor Of Robert (Bob) Farias Fall River, Ma, 1946 - Lexington, Ma, 2019 Educator, Coach And Mentor Coach Farias Was A Teacher In The Lexington Public Schools For Over Four Decades At Adams And Harrington Elementary And Directed The Alternative Choice Education (A.c.e.) Program At Lexington High School. He Was Head Coach Of The Lexington High Boys Varsity Basketball Team For 41 Years, Won A State Championship In 1978, 18 Middlesex League Titles And Inducted Into 6 Hall Of Fames As A Player And Coach. He Was An Inspiration And Mentor To Thousands On These Courts Running Basketball Camps And The Summer League. His Passion, Dedication, Quick Wit And Impact On These Courts, In The Classroom And In The Lexington Community Transcends Generations And Will Continue To Live On In All The Lives He Touched. Dedicated In 2021.
